segments.text: to Hispanic employees, and did this treatment change over time?
Well, actually, at the onset, let's talk about the dining hall, for instance.
Way back there, the only thing they hired were people from Mexico, for some reason or another, because they were considered
good cooks, I guess, and good workers.
So you're saying the dining hall was mostly spent?
Yeah, I would say that 100% were people from Mexico.
And they did a heck of a good job, and they took good care of the students.
They were also cooks.
you know, salad people, which I don't know what you call that, but they made salads for people.
And they were also people who took up, well, cleaned the mess afterwards, you know, they were KP people, bus boys and what have you.
And... What about managing the place?
The manager also was from Mexico, by the name of Juan
Peña, I think his name was.
Peña, Juan Peña.
He was also.
But then something happened.
The state legislature passed a law that non-citizens could not work in a state-owned institution or state-operated institution.
So abruptly, they were all let out.
And so then they hired an American
American citizens, and they hired Hispanics and blacks and Anglos and everything else.
But I mean, everybody was treated well there.
As far as the overall campus is concerned, there weren't too many opportunities for Hispanics to work on the campus.
I don't know why.
Even right now, the percentage of Hispanic workers is very, very low.
I mean, you've hardly seen them.
And I know that a lot of them are qualified.
And even when I was there, when I was there at operation manager, I hired Hispanics to work as students mostly.
office workers.
I had several Hispanic office workers.
And you could see quite a few office workers of Hispanic origin also on the campus.
But as far as a male worker is concerned, Hispanic worker, you hardly see them on the campus.
This is one thing I don't understand.
And I think that exists now.
Other than student Hispanics, Hispanic
Male workers are very scarce on the campus.
I noticed that.
I was there 52 years.
And during all those years, it never did improve, as far as I'm concerned.
Really?
Never did.
I don't know why.
I don't understand it, because they are good workers.
Did you ever work with any other Spanx?
Hardly ever, I assume?
What do you mean, did I work with them?
In your job.
Did I work some of them?
Work with them.
Yeah, I had real good workers.
Yeah, I had Isidro Lopez, who worked with me for years.
Actually, he was a foreman under me, and he did a good job.
Very dedicated.
I mean, he'd be the first set and the last leave.
If you needed him on a Saturday or Sunday, he was there, no question.
And I'm sure that your Uncle Paul, who also was foreman at the dining hall, he can tell you about the Hispanic workers.
But he would have trouble with these, you know, with some of these other workers of other nationalities who just didn't.
And you can see it now.
You take, right now, your hardworking people or your people from Mexico and your Hispanic people, they're working.
But I have people here somehow, I don't know what it is, we just don't want to work anymore.
First thing they want to know is how much you're going to pay them, and of course that's a good thing, but how many breaks you get during the day and how long you break, stuff like that.
Whereas you, one of these Mexican workers,
They'll work right now.
They don't ask those kind of questions.
But getting back to your original question about how to, I think your question was, how did A&M react to the Hispanic workers or something like that?
How did they treat them?
Was it equal treatment for them?
Well, there were some, of course, there's pros and cons here.
Where I stood, I thought some were treated unjustly.
But the overall administrator did not think so.
They had some other overrulia, and that was it.
But you hardly see any Hispanic foreman anywhere in charge of anything.
And there's never been a large influx
of expanding workers that ain't them, male that is.
And I doubt if there are too many female.

Whether that's because there's not enough skill amongst them, because some of these jobs do require skill, like they need carpenters, painters, electricians, and air conditioned people, and they're all Anglos.
But even today, would you say that at managerial levels,
It hasn't really changed much.
There really aren't many Hispanics at all.
No, it has not changed much at all.
I can tell you that right now.
It has not changed.
Well, how did your coworkers, non-Hispanic coworkers, respond to you or to other Hispanics working with them?
Was there a problem there?
Was that an equal footing, I would say?
You're asking how did I get along with my...
Anglo co-workers?
Yes.
Well, I got along fine with them.

Actually, when you come right down to it, you could call the whole system co-workers, that is the wage people, that is the so-called non-faculty people, because y'all work together for the university.
And in my capacity, since chemistry was the largest department,
largest department on campus, we required more of the physical plant services than any other department.
And as a result, I got to see those people more and I had a chance to work with them and I found that they were very good to me.
And I tried to be as equal as them, be the same as them.
We worked together.
And even now, when I'm retired, and I'm retired, I meet them on the street.
Boy, they don't hesitate to go and shake my hand.
We talk about it all the time.
So they actually got along fine.
So I got along with them all right.
Being Hispanic, it seemed to me that they have that same attitude toward other Hispanics.
So it might be that maybe, I don't know what it is.
I just can't put my finger on it, why the Hispanics are not being hired more over there.
Let me ask you about, I know you were involved on the grievances committee.
Can you tell me in what capacity you served the grievances committee?
And if there were any special incidences that have an impact on employees at Texas A&M that you feel you can comment on because of that experience?
Well, the problem here is that I did not deal with Hispanics on this.
But I was the only Hispanic.
on this so-called panel.
And instead of taking the grievance, a person taking his grievances to court, he would take it to this panel.
And this panel, from this panel, he could pick out someone to defend him.
And then the other people that were against him could pick out someone to defend them.
And then from the panel, they had a group that would act as judge and jury.
And so they'd hear us.
And the university would accept that recommendation.
And to me, it was fair.
It was fair.
I think it was real fair.
Not all that.
The guy who felt that he was done an injustice could go out and get a lawyer instead of getting one of us.
And I saw that only at one time, that's all.
And to me, it was effective in that

actually there was one incident where one fellow was more or less fired and he felt that they did it just when he got hurt on the job and the hospital was pretty expensive so I represented him and as a result of the hearing and
And the discussion that went on, actually he was reinstated and they paid for the hospitalization.
And if I'm thinking right, I think he's still there.
But they had let him go.
They had let him go.
He was fired, period.
And this is what this grievance was all about.
But I never did.
Since there's not too many Hispanics, well, no problem with none there, hardly.
Very few at that time.
Now, I've been gone four years.
Now, they might have had a large group there, but I doubt it.
I don't think so.
Because I don't see them, and I don't hear anybody that I know tell me they work at A&M except one or two, and that's it.
The same one or two that have been there 20 years, they're the same ones there now.
Something else I'd like you to comment on along those lines.
You were instrumental in the first affirmative action program at Texas A&M.
Can you tell me how you got that going and what exactly was entailed, what it produced?
Well, actually, I got this letter from President Runner asking me if I would serve with this committee of four to come up with an affirmative action program for the university since
just about every other university on the campus, I mean the state of Texas had one except us.
When was this?
Peter had been, oh God, maybe ten years ago, I guess, that's a good rough guess.
That's when it was, Pratt & Rudder was still, no, no, it wasn't Pratt & Rudder.
Vanderbilt?
No, no, Williamson.
Okay.
Chained after it was Pratt & Williamson, that's right, right after, yeah.
So that had been about 10 years ago.
And so I thought I'd be honored to serve on it.
And so the purpose of that was to make sure that the university would hire a fair percentage of Anglos and Blacks.
And that the university would make a strong effort to hire Spanish and Blacks.
And it was an intricate thing to deal with.
And I don't know whether it's had any impact on hiring Hispanics, because I thought for sure that it would.
But as far as I know, I don't think so.
But the thing is that this thing also applied for the faculty.
And of course, they hired quite a few Hispanic faculty.
And that's what I'm saying.
If the Hispanic has some sort of preparation or some sort of an academic background, I think he can be hired.
But sometimes I wonder whether the applicants that are turned down, whether they're qualified or not to accept this particular job they want.
And I think the affirmative action is a good thing to have.
if they go ahead and carry it out like it's supposed to, or if they were to implement it like it should be, but I don't think they are.
Actually, one of the affirmative action officers that left about four or five years ago told me that she left because the university was not strong on implementing the affirmative action.

you know uh whatever affirmative action uh program and uh so i really can't tell you whether it's done any good or not peter uh i doubt if it has of course uh president reagan didn't want that in the country i don't think i think he wanted to get rid of it but they still have it at nm
And according to newspapers, A&M is doing all they can to recruit minorities, not only in school, but also in jobs.
And I don't know just how well they've done.
I don't know.
Let me change gears once again and ask you about something that's a little more recent.
The last 10 or 15 years has seen sort of a new wave of immigration from Mexico.
How do you think this has affected the Hispanic community in Bryan?
Have these people generally been accepted?
Is there a pro and con to this issue?
What's your response?
Explain that again, Peter.
I kind of see what it is.
You're talking about people from Mexico now, right?
Right.
The immigrants, the aliens coming over.
How has that affected this community?
Okay, you're talking about the working people.
You're not talking about... Well, I don't think there's too many of the other.
Okay, all right.
Actually, Pete...
Peter, I think it's helped the community.
And I think that people, leading citizens of the community think that without these people, they couldn't have accomplished what they have thus far, like for instance, roadworks.
Because of the labor force.
The labor force.
At A&M, you take at A&M, all this big building program they've got going there.
If you go there, you'll notice that so many of them, the big majority of them, that are doing the hard work and are doing the heavy semen work are Hispanics.
And they're the ones that are doing a lot of the so-called bricklaying, doing a lot of semen work, this fine semen work.
A lot of them are doing this fine hard work.
And you can see that in Brian, too.
In Brian, you take younger brothers who
who is one of the largest road contractors around here, he'll tell you right now that without those people, he couldn't keep up with his deadline.
He couldn't meet his deadline.
And if you drive any place while they're doing this, you'll find that they are
that there's a lot of these people from Mexico that are there doing this hard work.
A lot of these people do a lot of work for the city of Bryan.
The city of Bryan can't find American citizens to do this work, so they have to rely on these amnesty people to do that.
And they're the one that do your farm work for you.
They're the one that clean your cow sheds and your horse sheds.
They do a lot of work.
And now, as you know, a lot of our own here, I don't think the black community want to do that work anymore.
They figure that you don't see black people doing that kind of work no more.
They used to, but not anymore.
They don't feel that they should.
And so if they're going to do it, then your wage is going to go way up.
And these people that are working hard, they're working for the way you said they are now, whatever it is.
I get a lot of minimum wage at the beginning.
Do you think that there's been any negative response, perhaps in light of the fact that some would say this is sort of bringing a rising Hispanic community a step back?
It's an added weight.
Do you see it in that light?
And that in way to the Hispanic community?
Yes.
Well, I think that I don't think that the Hispanic community feel that these Amnesty workers are taking their jobs away from them.
Because they probably won't do that job either because they speak well English, they speak good English, and they can get better jobs working in stores and places like that.
To me, I think it helps because, especially the Hispanic business people, because a lot of these people go to the Hispanic business people because they can communicate with them.
And the people who are in some sort of recreation, the Hispanic people, these people patronize them because they commute.
No, I don't think so.
I think that the Hispanic community considers them an advantage.
being here.
I know that in the past you've worked with naturalization of aliens.
Can you tell me something about that?
What exactly was involved?
Well, actually, many, when we came back from the war, from overseas, at that time it finally hit me that it was not fair that
the parents of these boys that went overseas and fought for this country, and many of them didn't even come back, that their parents had no rights, couldn't even vote.
And they've been here for 50 years, 20, 40 years, and still didn't have a right to vote.
And actually, those that were real poor had not even right for welfare, not even right for anything.
And the only way that they could
have this right by becoming a citizen.
And so we decided to go ahead and set up schools.
We went to the they had a lawyer organization here.
I forget the name of it.
And we went to them and they got together with the American Legion and said they would help us as far as the lawyers were concerned to write up some of the
things that they need to know, and the questions and answers and so forth.
Kind of a textbook in tablet form.
And they wrote this textbook for us.
Because the one from, I got a textbook from San Antonio Immigration Service, from Immigration Services in San Antonio.
They're very complicated, it's only English.
But they did it in English.
But we found a group here that would be able to transfer.
They translated in Spanish.
So we had both of them.
So they had both of them.
So then we got together.
Your uncle Paul and I got together and studied this thing, I mean, extensively until we learned about it ourselves.
And then this information, we started having classes and passed it on to them.
And they were very eager to learn.
They learned.
And not only that, we had to go to a lot of trouble to establish a residence for them.
A lot of them came here in 1902 and couldn't prove it.
So we had the right to places where they worked or take them over there.
I mean, we made many trips out to Braggers Bottom, Waco, to San Antonio, to places like that, the way they
They entered, and people that knew them, and we got affidavits from these people that they worked for.
And that's how we did it.
And it was a hassle.
But we made them into citizens that way.
And we'd take them to San Antonio, and they'd pass a test.
And then when they'd, right here in Braddus County, they'd be sworn in.
One time we swore in about 30 at one time.
Wow.
Old people, and they answered the question, and...
They became citizens, and they were just thrilled to be able to vote, to have a voice in the government.
And of course, the sons and daughters that were very proud of their parents because they were citizens.
And so we did this.
And that, I think, helped the community.
And I was always very grateful to these lawyers that started this, that helped us.
did not turn us down when we went to ask for their help.
They did it pre-charge.
They didn't charge anything.
And they'd make several trips to see how we were doing to make sure that we were doing it right.
And they liked what they saw.
What about today?
I think you've also been involved in some of this today.
There's a lot of aliens that, with the recent amnesty program, also needed to verify it.
Well, the only way I'm involved there, Peter, is that
I'm able to write letters for them.

You know, I write letters for them and also helpful fill out because when they go to this place where they're supposed to be processed, they'll give them a blank and say, you fill it or find somebody to fill it for you.
Well, it's me they find or somebody like me and we fill these blanks based on what they tell us.
And then we have a lot of this required notarization
and some required letter attachment of some sort, and we do that.
That's the only, that's the extent I'm involved in, but we do it, we don't charge anybody, we never charge anybody.
We never have, you know.
And so, and then anyway we can help them.
Sometimes they have problems in Mexico, and, or somebody wants to go to Mexico, we write a letter on their behalf to the Immigration and Activation Service,
and they'll give us what you call an emergency permit for them to go and come back.
And that's the kind of thing we're involved in right now.
Other than that, that's it.

What about political action within the Hispanic community, specifically politicians that come from it, the way that local politicians have addressed the Hispanic community or tried to gain support from it?
Can you comment on this, what it's been like?
Well, unlike many years ago, the politicians today are really going after the Hispanic vote because there's so many of them here now.
And because of that, the Hispanics are better off because they
somehow or other, in certain areas, outnumber the Anglos and the blacks in some of these voting precincts.
And when these officials get elected, they tend to remember that the Hispanic voted for them and they pass legislature that benefits Hispanic.
But the Hispanic's been very active, too.
If they see a candidate that
that will serve the community well and will not forget them while they'll go out and stump for him and do what they can to help get him elected.
But you don't see any of this, they're not after, they're not in for selfish purposes.
They just want a good guy that is reasonable,
that will understand, that will be somewhat sympathetic towards them.
And that plot, that's it.
That's all they want.
And to me, I've been with these Aspani for so long.
To me, the attitude is that if this guy does a good job this year, then I'll vote for him next time around.
That's the extent of the interest in politics.
That's it.
Has this always been the case?
To me, it's always been that way here.
Now you've got a few guys that, you know,
I think they want something out of it, but not too many of them.
They're obscured.
What about Hispanic candidates themselves?
Hispanic candidates themselves, how are they fair to Brian?
Well, we just somehow have never gotten the right people to run for office, Peter.
The people that normally run...
somehow, or not, let me change that a little bit.
I just don't think that, they think they're qualified, but they're not.
And so they run and they keep running and they don't get elected, then they wonder why they don't get elected.
What's happening to us is that
The Hispanic that is qualified and that could make a good candidate or could be an asset to his community, to Hispanic, he's not here.
He gets his education and he leaves town because this town doesn't have anything to offer him or doesn't hire him.
This is why I know one of the members of the Brian B., Roy Marine to be specific, they had a...
an opening here for a school teacher.
And he wanted to come back to Bryan.
He's an Odessa teacher's school.
And he wrote a letter, a real nice letter, and he made a personal visit down here.
And they gave him hope, but he never heard from them anymore.
And yet, they didn't have any Hispanic teachers.
I think only one at that time, or maybe two.
Two Herrera sisters, I think.
And so Roy never came back to Bryan.
And I know that Fred wanted to teach here in Bryan, and he never could get on.
I don't know whether he made a real effort, but he said that when he talked to some of the people, they kind of indicated that he didn't have much of a chance.
This is our problem.
The people that are qualified to run for office are not around.
Just close your eyes and think how many Hispanics have graduated from high school here in Bryan, raised here in Bryan, that graduated from A&M or University of Houston or Sam Houston.
They're not here in Bryan.
There's only one that finally came back to Bryan, and that's Daniel Hernandez, who got his law degree from Georgetown.
He's back.
But other than that, the rest of them are not here.
They're not here.

But until these people that are finishing, until these Hispanics that are from here, that were born and raised here, and after they graduate from the college can find something here, then we're going to have this problem.
We're only going to have a blue collar running for position, and he's not qualified for it.
And the people know it.
He doesn't get elected.
He doesn't have it.
Well, that's a good time for me to ask you this question, then.
What do you think are the relevant issues in Brian's Hispanic community today?
What are the things that, if you look forward, that you think need to be addressed or that
Is this mainly it right here, the fact that it's hard to retain a lot of inner support in the Hispanic community because there's just not that much to offer?
Well, actually, also another thing, too, Peter, we're not prepared, really, some of us, to run for office.
We don't seem to want to prepare ourselves.
We don't have a, we've never had, within our community, road models.
The kind that would set a good example for you.
And we have road models, but they're not here.
You never see them, you never hear from them, and they never address our children.
People don't know.
When they come to town, they're strangers, you know?
And I think that
The Hispanic family cites that the parents do not encourage a complete education.
You know what I mean?
They say, look, go to school.
Soon you can read and write.
That's enough.
Get your job.
Learn to be a mechanic or a plumber or go out and work on construction.
And that's what's happening.
And the first thing you know, the boy's 20 years old, he gets married, that's it.
That's the end of it.
And then later on, he wants to run for something.
He's not going to get elected, Peter.
I mean, it's our fault too, you know.
We need people that will stay here and succeed so that these kids
can see what success is like, can see what a successful young man looks like.
And of course, we've got a few, but not hardly.
And those somehow or other seem to obscure themselves from the majority of Hispanics.
They seem to want to assimilate into the American culture, more or less, because they figure, well, that's where the money's at.
I mean, who owns a corporation here in Hispanic, you know, families?
Nobody.
In other words, they're going to be seen with those people because those are the people that are going to make them a living.
And they don't worry too much about us, you know.
That's the problem.
Well, I think that about wraps it up.
Do you have anything further to add?
Well, no, Peter, I just wasn't too prepared for this, but I just gave it to you from the heart.
I know it may not be exactly what you wanted.
You know, I've been around here in this town for 74 years, and there's a lot in my mind that I could say, but it'll take a long time, and I know y'all don't have that kind of time.
But I've seen so much, and one of these days I'll sit down and write the story of my life, and then you'll see more of what you wanted to see.
You'll see probably not more of what you wanted to see, but you'll see what you wanted to see tonight or hear from me tonight.
But I hope this will be of some help.
I'm sure it will, and I look forward to that.
If nothing else, this concludes the interview, December 5th, 1989.
I'm sorry to interrupt you, but if there's anything else I can do for you, let me know.
Okay, thank you.
